The paper deals with information theory and communication networks, which suggests that it belongs to the cs.IT (Information Theory) category. The paper specifically focuses on discrete memoryless multimessage multicast networks (DM-MMNs), which are a type of communication network, making cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) another likely category. The paper also mentions wireless erasure networks, which could fall under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The paper's use of Renyi divergence as a proof technique suggests that it could also belong to cs.MM (Multimedia), as Renyi divergence has been used in multimedia applications. Finally, the paper's focus on achieving tight cut-set bounds could also place it in the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) category.
